                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p>
                                        <add>??? ?? יום א ז"ך סיון קול מבשר ואומר ???</add>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>
                                        <add>אל ה"ב המושלם נעים ??? ישראל ?? יצחק ??? בעיר
                                                  פילאדאלפיה עא</add>
                              </p>
                              <p>to institute the Portuguese <add>הנה שמעתי מאחורי הפרגוד, וגם זכיתי
                                                  לקרוא בספר אקסידענט, ??? ???</add> through whole<lb/>
                                        <placeName><hi rend="underline">America</hi></placeName>.
                                        with out distintione<add>?</add> of <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >Native Land</hi><lb/> whether, <hi
                                                  rend="underline">Pole</hi>, <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >German</hi>, <hi rend="underline">English</hi>, or<lb/>
                                        <sic><hi rend="underline">Americane</hi></sic>,</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)"><addressee>Revd Sir Mr Leeser</addressee>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I am in great hope, that, the assembly,<lb/> will
                                        cause, my freedom in giving <add>?</add><lb/> my advice
                                                  <sic>gratio</sic>, and prove a Body<lb/> who is
                                        not much learned mere, who are to<lb/> assemble very soon,
                                        please, to lay<lb/> my Letter before the Assembly</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>and also to put it in <hi rend="underline">print</hi>, in your<lb/>
                                        valuable Book the Occident. and<lb/> have the goodness, to
                                        inform me<lb/> of the result, of your Meeting.<lb/> I
                                                  <sic>wuld</sic> have written, in the English<lb/>
                                        Language <sic>intyrly</sic>, but, I<lb/> can't express
                                        myself so well with<lb/> English language, as in the
                                        Hebrew<lb/> therefore, I was compelled by<lb/> persuasion of
                                        my friends to <sic>adress</sic><lb/> my letter to you, in
                                        the Holy Langu,,<lb/>,,age, and hope that, the awe also
                                        form<lb/> of Prayers, and also, the <add>אשר המה מתגוררים פה
                                                  אמריקא, ויושבים על כס ההוראה , להורות את</add> of
                                        Reading<lb/> fore ever, and ever, Amen.</p>
                              <p>
                                        <add>בית ישראל, הדרך שר ילכו בו, ואת המעשה אשר ???, מתאפסים
                                                  יחד</add>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <hi rend="underline">Amen</hi>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <sic>adress</sic>
                                        <hi rend="indent(7)">I am your most Respected</hi>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <persName role="author">Isaac Moses Slatky</persName>
                                        <hi rend="indent(6)">and <sic>devouted</sic> for the
                                                  Israe,,</hi>
                              </p>
                              <p>care of Mr <hi rend="indent(7)">litsch faith <sic>voor</sic> ever
                                                  and</hi></p>
                              <p>
                                        <persName>E. Bernheimer</persName>
                                        <hi rend="indent(7)">ever.</hi>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <placeName>
                                                  <hi rend="underline">Buffalo N. Y. </hi>
                                        </placeName>
                                        <hi rend="indent(7)">
                                                  <persName role="author">Isaac M. Slatky</persName>
                                        </hi>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)"> care <add>?</add> of</p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">the Buffalo Hebrew</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">Congregation.</p>
                              <p rend="A note in Hebrew is written sideways in left margin"/>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>Revd</p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p>Editor of the Occident</p>
                              <p>
                                        <placeName>
                                                  <hi rend="underline">Philadelphia.Pa</hi>
                                        </placeName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="5"/>
                              <p>The interesting thing about this<lb/> letter which comes from a
                                        pious soul<lb/> though a befuddled mind, is the
                                                  <sic>naivite</sic><lb/> with which orthodox Jews
                                        regarded<lb/> reformers. This man thought that<lb/> they
                                        were aching for a change, any<lb/> change</p>
                              <pb n="6"/>
                              <p><placeName>Buffalo</placeName>, <date>Sunday, 14 Sivan, 5609</date>
                                                  [<date>June 1849</date>]</p>
                              <p>To the accomplished etc. etc</p>
                              <p>I heard from indirect sources, and also have read in the<lb/>
                                        Occident, that scholars and rabbis living here in
                                                  <placeName>America</placeName>, and<lb/> who sit
                                        on the seat of instruction to teach the children of
                                                  <placeName>Israel</placeName> the<lb/> way to go
                                        and the thing to do, will soon gather in assembly.<lb/>
                                        Although I have not attained to the destruction of being one
                                        of the<lb/> delegates, for I am a stranger here, a guest who
                                        seeks no more<lb/> than lodgings, and cannot compare with
                                        you; nevertheless,<lb/> I cannot refrain, and shut my mouth.
                                        I want to know why<lb/> and wherefore. In this great cry I,
                                        the youngest among the<lb/> families of
                                                  <placeName>Israel</placeName>, agree with the
                                        learned <persName>Mr. S. Abraham</persName><lb/> with regard
                                        to everything he pointed out in the Occident of<lb/> last
                                        month. Your Honor knows that to the customs of our<lb/>
                                        fathers one may not add, nor detract from them. Then
                                        again,<lb/> my soul wants to know how it is possible to
                                        imagine<lb/> changing the prayers now established; to
                                        distort the<lb/> established rules of
                                                  <persName>Ezra</persName> the Scribe [his memory
                                        for a<lb/> blessing], with whom were many prophets, and
                                        whose<lb/> actions were undertaken at God's command and
                                                  <sic>insperation</sic>.<lb/> How can we,
                                        therefore, consider the reduction of the number<lb/> called
                                        up to the Torah on every holy <date>Sabbath</date> from
                                        the<lb/> number severe and one <hi rend="underline"
                                                  ><add>?</add></hi>. They may be wise, but<lb/>
                                        they do not know how to do good. All they can do is to
                                        come<lb/> together and place a yoke and a burden upon us.
                                        They<lb/> have a sword in their hand to cut down the tree of
                                        the<lb/> knowledge of good, and to change the traditions of
                                        our</p>
                              <pb n="7"/>
                              <p>sages [their memory for a blessing] and prophets<lb/> [their soul
                                        rest in the bag of life]. I therefore come with<lb/> a plea
                                        and request to your Great Honor not to<lb/> obey the priest
                                        who comes to perform the service of<lb/> the high priest in
                                        the holy place, and like a poor<lb/> man on <date><hi
                                                  rend="underline">Passover</hi></date>
                                        <del>who</del> begs for a piece of <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >bread</hi> to<lb/> support his breaking heart,
                                        thus changing the order of<lb/>
                                        <sic>of</sic> purity and holiness, to pray in a strange
                                        language,<lb/> and perverted speech. What is this strange
                                        service<lb/> which we, the congregation of
                                                  <placeName>Israel</placeName>, the witnesses of<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Sinai</placeName>, the descendants of
                                                  <persName>Abraham</persName>, must never,
                                        never<lb/> God forbid, do this?</p>
                              <p>My hand is still stretched out, and my quick pen<lb/> continues to
                                        speak, to be a good pleader and intercessor,<lb/> to speak
                                        righteousness for those who are about to<lb/> meet in the
                                        shadow of fine perfume. Who is the first<lb/> who began to
                                        change our holy language for a foreign one? And<lb/> seeking
                                        one's people's good, for the remnant of
                                                  <placeName>Israel</placeName> who do<lb/> no evil,
                                        (one understands that) the scattered grapes of
                                                  <persName>Ephraim</persName><lb/> are better than
                                        the entire crop of <persName><hi rend="underline"
                                                  >Yahuda</hi></persName>*. Outside of the
                                                  lang<add>?</add><lb/> is there no wisdom in it.
                                        Ah, to teach these <hi rend="underline">goyim</hi> we
                                        have<lb/> numerous commentaries on the Torah and the
                                        commandments, so<lb/> what more do we have to call out to
                                        God, the Lord of Hosts,<lb/> the God of
                                                  <placeName>Israel</placeName>. We have six volumes
                                        of <hi rend="underline">Gemara</hi>,<lb/> and ethical books,
                                        and legal works of the elder and younger<lb/>
                                        legalists—wealth of mind. We have no portion or
                                        inheritance</p>
                              <p>*Evidently this scatter brain means that the least of the Hebrew is
                                        superior to<lb/> the most of the German-Jewish culture.</p>
                              <pb n="8"/>
                              <p>in new covenants. Why then are Jewish children taught<lb/> to go in
                                        foreign ways, contrary to our holy Law. My<lb/> heart, my
                                        heart! How great is my pain, and my<lb/> eyes shed tears
                                        because of the breach of my people</p>
                              <p>But! I have a good plan, that seems to me<lb/> excellent. If you
                                        want to take my advice, let it be<lb/> as you say, change
                                        the ordinances of the sages and<lb/> at the same time remain
                                        God-fearing, Create a new<lb/> tradition among the Jews who
                                        live in <placeName>America</placeName></p>
                              <pb n="9"/>
                              <p rend="align(center)">
                                        <hi rend="underline">On last page of the Letter</hi>
                              </p>
                              <p>Torah</p>
                              <p>Till the coming of the Messiah, soon in our<lb/> day. So may it be
                                        God's will, and let us say</p>
                              <p>
                                        <hi rend="underline">Amen</hi>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="On margin"/>
                              <p>
                                        <hi rend="underline">P. S.</hi>
                              </p>
                              <p>This moment I spoke with the president of the<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Buffalo</placeName> congregation, and pleaded
                                        with him to send<lb/> to the place of your meeting. At the
                                        moment who could<lb/> not give me a <del>proper</del>
                                        satisfactory reply—not<lb/> till he talks to the members of
                                        the congregation. Then<lb/> we shall see about his
                                        plans...</p>
                              <p>
                                        <persName role="author">S. M. S.</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>from <placeName><hi rend="underline">Posen</hi></placeName></p>
